	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>SNES Hyper Zone 3D mode &amp; Famicom 3D glasses</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Hey, folks.  JLukas discovered on <em>The Cutting Room Floor</em> ( <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="https://tcrf.net/HyperZone">https://tcrf.net/HyperZone</a><!-- m --> ) that this game had a hidden 3-D mode that alternated Left and Right eye views, but today I guessed that this game wouldn't just implement such a thing and leave the shutter signals inside the SFC.  So I probed the joystick ports and found the 3-D glasses shutter signal!<br /><br /><img src="http://chrismcovell.com/images/Hyperzone_3D_DiscoverySm.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br />You could also leave a Famicom 3-D game running and connect the FC 3D glasses to it while playing on the SNES; however, Hyper Zone does have some slowdown when multiple sprites appear on screen along with their shots, causing the game to slow down, and L/R alternating to skip.  This will invert the 3D effect each time this happens.  So, wiring up the FC 3D system to the SNES/SFC as shown above will give a rock-solid 3-D effect.  It is pretty cool to see SNES mode 7 in 3D.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


